### PRA*S*NA I, ADHYÂYA 5, KA*ND*IKÂ 11.

1\. Referring to deaths and births, they declare that the impurity of
Sapi*nd*as lasts ten days; excepting officiating priests, men who have
performed the initiatory ceremony of a Soma-sacrifice, and students of
the Veda. <span id="fr_888"></span>[1](#fn_888.md)

2\. But amongst Sapi*nd*as Sapi*nd*a-relationship (extends) to the
seventh person. <span id="fr_889"></span>[2](#fn_889.md)

3\. (If children die) before the completion of the seventh month or
before teething, (the relatives) shall bathe. <span
id="fr_890"></span>[3](#fn_890.md)

4\. In (the case of a child) that dies before the completion of its
third year or before teething, offerings of funeral cakes and water are
not prescribed, and one should not burn its (body); <span
id="fr_891"></span>[4](#fn_891.md)

5\. Nor when unmarried maidens die.

6\. Some do it in the case of married daughters. <span
id="fr_892"></span>[6](#fn_892.md)

7\. That (is done) in order to gain the good-will <span
id="fr_893"></span>[7](#fn_893.md)

<span id="page_178">p. 178</span>

of the people. Women are considered to have no business with the sacred
texts.

8\. 'The relatives of unmarried women become pure after three days. But
the uterine brothers become pure by (following) the rule mentioned
before.' <span id="fr_894"></span>[8](#fn_894.md)

9\. Moreover, the great-grandfather, the grand-father, the father,
oneself, the uterine brothers, the son by a wife of equal caste, the
grandson, (and) the great-grandson--these they call Sapi*nd*as, but not
the (great-grandson's) son;--and amongst these a son and a son's son
(together with their father are) sharers of an undivided oblation. <span
id="fr_895"></span>[9](#fn_895.md)

10\. The sharers of divided oblations they call Sakulyas. <span
id="fr_896"></span>[10](#fn_896.md)

<span id="page_179">p. 179</span>

11\. If no other (relations) are living, the property (of a deceased
male) descends to them (the Sapi*nd*as). <span
id="fr_897"></span>[11](#fn_897.md)

12\. On failure of Sapi*nd*as, the Sakulyas (inherit). <span
id="fr_898"></span>[12](#fn_898.md)

13\. On failure of them, the teacher who (holds the place of a
spiritual) father, a pupil, or an officiating priest shall take
it, <span id="fr_899"></span>[13](#fn_899.md)

14\. On failure of them, the king. Let him give that property to persons
well-versed in the three Vedas. <span id="fr_900"></span>[14](#fn_900.md)

15\. But the king should never take for himself the property of a
Brâhma*n*a. <span id="fr_901"></span>[15](#fn_901.md)

16\. Now they quote also (the following verse): The property of a
Brâhma*n*a destroys (him who

<span id="page_180">p. 180</span>

takes it), together with sons and grandsons; poison kills one man only.
(Therefore) they do not declare poison to be (the worst) poison. The
property of a Brâhma*n*a is called (the worst) poison.'

17\. If a birth and a death occur together, one. and the same period of
ten (days and) nights (shall serve for both).

18\. Now if (other deaths or births) happen before the completion of the
ten (days and) nights (of impurity), the first period of ten (days and)
nights (shall suffice, provided the new cause of impurity occurs) before
the end of the ninth day. <span id="fr_902"></span>[18](#fn_902.md)

19\. On a birth, indeed, the parents (alone) become impure during ten
days. <span id="fr_903"></span>[19](#fn_903.md)

20\. Some (declare that) the mother (alone becomes impure), because
(people) avoid (lying-in women alone). <span
id="fr_904"></span>[20](#fn_904.md)

21\. Others (say that) the father (alone becomes impure) because the
semen is the chief cause (of the generation). <span
id="fr_905"></span>[21](#fn_905.md)

22\. For sons who were born without mothers, are mentioned in the
revealed texts.

23\. But (the correct opinion is that) both the parents (become impure)
because they are equally connected (with the event).

<span id="page_181">p. 181</span>

24\. But when a death (has happened, the relatives of the deceased),
allowing the youngest to begin, shall pass their sacrificial threads
over the right shoulder and under the left arm, descend into the water
at a bathing-place, submerge (their bodies), emerge (out of the water),
ascend the bank, sip water, pour out libations for the (deceased,
repeating the last four acts) severally three times thereafter, ascend
the bank, sip water, touch a coal, water or the like at the door of
their house, and sit during ten days on mats, eating food that does not
contain pungent condiments or salt. <span
id="fr_906"></span>[24](#fn_906.md)

25\. (Let him perform) a funeral sacrifice on the eleventh or the
twelfth (day). <span id="fr_907"></span>[25](#fn_907.md)

26\. In (performing) the remaining rites (one should) conform to (the
customs of) the people. <span id="fr_908"></span>[26](#fn_908.md)

27\. In case of a (death) let him also keep (a period of impurity) for
(persons who are) not (his) Sapi*nd*as, according to the degree of
nearness, three (days and) nights, a day and a night, one day and so
forth, <span id="fr_909"></span>[27](#fn_909.md)

<span id="page_182">p. 182</span>

28\. For a teacher, a sub-teacher (upâdhyâya), and their sons, three
(days and) nights, <span id="fr_910"></span>[28](#fn_910.md)

29\. Likewise for officiating priests, <span
id="fr_911"></span>[29](#fn_911.md)

30\. Let hire keep. on account of a pupil, for one who has the same
spiritual guide, for a fellow-student (sabrahma*k*ârin) three (days and)
nights, one day and a night, one day and so forth (as periods of
impurity). <span id="fr_912"></span>[30](#fn_912.md)

31\. On a miscarriage females (remain impure) as many (days and) nights
as months (elapsed after conception). <span
id="fr_913"></span>[31](#fn_913.md)

32\. If he unintentionally touches the corpse of a stranger, he becomes
at once pure after bathing dressed in his clothes.

33\. (If he does it) intentionally, (he will remain impure) during three
(days and) nights.

34\. And (the same rules apply if he touches a woman) during her
courses. <span id="fr_914"></span>[34](#fn_914.md)

35\. A son who is born from (intercourse with a temporarily unclean
woman) becomes an Abhi*s*asta. Thereby the penances (to be performed) by
him have been explained.

<span id="page_183">p. 183</span>

36\. On touching one who sells the Veda, a sacrificial post, an outcast,
a funeral pile, a dog, or a *K*a*nd*âla he shall bathe. <span
id="fr_915"></span>[36](#fn_915.md)

37\. Now if a worm is produced in an open wound that is filled with pus
and sanies, how shall, in that case, a penance be performed? <span
id="fr_916"></span>[37](#fn_916.md)

38\. He who is bitten by a worm will become pure on bathing (daily)
during three days and drinking (a mixture of) cow's urine, cowdung,
milk, sour milk, butter, and water boiled with Ku*s*a grass.

39\. He who has been touched by a dog shall bathe dressed in his
clothes; <span id="fr_917"></span>[39](#fn_917.md)

40\. Or he becomes pure by washing that spot (where he has been
touched), by touching it with fire, by (afterwards) again washing it and
his feet, and by sipping water.

41\. Now they quote also (the following verses): 'But a Brâhma*n*a who
has been bitten by a dog, is purified if he goes to a river that flows
into the ocean, (bathes there and) suppresses his breath one hundred
times and (afterwards) eats clarified butter. He will (also) become pure
at, once on bathing (in water brought) in golden or silver (vessels), or
in a cow's horn, or in new (earthen pots).' <span
id="fr_918"></span>[41](#fn_918.md)

